comments.message:
The "empty means everything" encoding is a bit counter-intuitive; I'd suggest at least putting a comment explaining it on the declaration of busBlacklist.

It also means that you'll end up with some pretty surprising results if someone does e.g.

```
{
  "buses": [
    ...
    {
      "bus": 3,
      "addresses": []
    },
    ...
  ]
}
```

The obvious reading of that is that no addresses on bus 3 should be skipped, but it'll end up skipping the entire bus instead.  I might argue for a slightly more explicit representation in the busBlacklist data structure, perhaps something like map<int, optional<set<int>>>, using nullopt to signal "all addresses" and leaving an empty set meaning the natural obvious thing ("no addresses").

We have been working on std::optional and want to clarify a thing. When user put:
{
  "buses": [
    ...
    {
      "bus": 3,
      "addresses": []
    },
    ...
  ]
}
Because this is a blocklist, we should assume that user want to block addresses on bus 3. If someone leaves addresses data empty, should we block an entire bus for the safety? In case someone just forgot to put addresses data.
